title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta M9  ( YOU SHOULD READ THIS BERETTA LOVERS!!!!!!  )
location: Italy or USA, Pennsylvania, United States
postcontent:
"The Italian Beretta is way better then the USA model !! " I've said this and really believed it.
"Why buy the USA model when the Italian one will last longer" oah yeah I thought so too. 

I highly favored the Italian model Beretta over the USA model for as long as I can remember and I'm sure a lot of you's have as well. In fact I still do but only for novelty reasons and that's just about it. I'm not a very Patriotic only buy American things type of guy, but I have some things to make you think about when buying your next Beretta M9 or 92fs. If you have ears attached to your head you've heard the story, but did you ever really think it through. 

When Beretta came to us to propose the Beretta M9 it was basically a prototype in our eyes. They though it was ready for the battle field and in fact is it strait out wasn't. Not only that it was far from it.  We made them change so many things before we even tested it. Like where the mag release button is, no it wasn't always where it is today, and where the safety is and also the fact that it decocks. that's just to name a few besides the magazines that the US helped Beretta with the design and production of after the magazine problems. also other little things like measurements of the gun itself, Ok ok I digress on that. If you didn't know now you do.

Fact is every time the US even suggested a change or even touched the Beretta it got better, and yes that is a fact!!  When they brought the Beretta to the US, it was basically a hunk of metal with an open slide that was very attractive to the eye and the US wanted to make it work. I didn't see or hear about the US suggesting even a 1 change on any other test weapon let alone help! all we did was complain about them during and after testing and told them what was wrong, but didn't suggest or try to help by any means.
The US told Beretta what to do with the firearm and gave them plenty of chances to get it right and straiten out the design. Even helped them with the measurements like I said before. 

The US was not stupid and saw something good and boy were they right. The us didn't Just help smooth out the edges they dam near designed the dam thing themselves. In all reality the Italian's should be trying to get there hands on the USA model not the other way around. Bottom line, if it wasn't for the US Beretta would be nowhere near or even close to what they are today!! our contract made them and we dam near made there gun.

"But Italy has a harder metal and aluminum" Think again, we have access to the most strongest metals known to mankind. Not saying there used on the beretta, but if that's the last statement anyone who loves Italian beretta's is holding on to I guess I just cut the string. Italy couldn't get the metals we could. oah and craftsmanship, well we crafted it! anything else?? we both use the same exact machinery as a matter a fact we ship them the machines we use, not the other way around. 

Well I think I got my point across. If you don't favor the USA model over the Italian one that is absolutely fine, but don't look down on or think anything less of the USA model. Both are great models. If I had to choose what model would outlast the other id have to go with the USA model and that's if I really had to choose. I own both in both blued and inox. All work great. the Italian model Inox turned yellow where the wear marks are as they did on my cousins after about 800 rounds but they still work great. That is he only problem I've came across with either model. If the USA model did that o boy forget about, no one would buy another one. Thank you for reading.     Now armslist on you Armslisters!!
